WEBVTT

1
00:03:04.054 --> 00:03:07.183
<i>So where are you?
You’re in some motel room.</i>

2
00:03:07.266 --> 00:03:10.394
<i>You just wake up,
and you’re in a motel room.</i>

3
00:03:10.478 --> 00:03:13.814
<i>There’s the key. It feels like maybe
it’s just the first time you’ve been there…</i>

4
00:03:13.898 --> 00:03:18.486
<i>but… perhaps you’ve been there for a week…</i>

5
00:03:18.569 --> 00:03:20.112
<i>three months.</i>

6
00:03:21.197 --> 00:03:23.407
<i>It’s kind of hard to say.
I don’t know.</i>

7
00:03:23.491 --> 00:03:25.808
<i>It’s just an anonymous room.</i>

8
00:03:27.244 --> 00:03:29.288
<i>It’s just an anonymous room.</i>

9
00:03:29.372 --> 00:03:31.373
<i>There’s nothing in the drawers.
But you look anyway.</i>

10
00:03:31.457 --> 00:03:36.378
<i>Nothing except the Gideon Bible,
which I, of course, read religiously.</i>

11
00:03:38.464 --> 00:03:42.967
<i>You know who you are,
and you know kind of all about yourself.</i>

12
00:03:43.052 --> 00:03:47.640
<i>But just for day-to-day stuff,
notes are really useful.</i>

13
00:03:48.974 --> 00:03:51.435
<i>Sammy Jankis had the same problem…</i>

14
00:03:51.519 --> 00:03:53.479
<i>but he really had no system.</i>

15
00:03:53.562 --> 00:03:55.940
<i>He wrote himself
a ridiculous amount of notes…</i>

16
00:03:56.023 --> 00:03:57.942
<i>but he’d get them all mixed up.</i>

17
00:03:58.025 --> 00:04:02.278
<i>You really do need a system
if you’re gonna make it work.</i>

18
00:04:04.740 --> 00:04:07.451
<i>You really need a system
if you’re gonna make it work.</i>

19
00:04:07.535 --> 00:04:10.579
<i>You kind of learn
to trust your own handwriting.</i>

20
00:04:10.663 --> 00:04:14.709
<i>That becomes an important part of your life.
You write yourself notes.</i>

21
00:04:14.792 --> 00:04:17.128
<i>Where you put your notes—
That also becomes important.</i>

22
00:04:17.712 --> 00:04:19.797
<i>You need a jacket that’s got
like six pockets in it.</i>

23
00:04:19.880 --> 00:04:22.091
<i>Particular pockets for particular things.</i>

24
00:04:22.174 --> 00:04:26.012
<i>You just kind of learn to know
where things go and how the system works.</i>

25
00:04:26.095 --> 00:04:30.141
<i>And you have to be wary of other people writing
stuff for you that is not gonna make sense…</i>

26
00:04:30.224 --> 00:04:32.184
<i>or is gonna lead you astray.</i>

27
00:04:32.268 --> 00:04:35.563
<i>I don’t know. I guess people try and take
advantage of somebody with this condition.</i>

28
00:04:36.564 --> 00:04:41.736
<i>If you have a piece
of information which is vital…</i>

29
00:04:41.819 --> 00:04:45.239
<i>writing on your body instead of
on a piece of paper can be the answer.</i>

30
00:04:45.322 --> 00:04:47.616
<i>It’s just a permanent way of keeping a note.</i>

31
00:04:54.790 --> 00:04:56.314
Who is this?

32
00:04:57.794 --> 00:04:59.962
You said we talked before.
I don’t remember that.

33
00:05:00.546 --> 00:05:03.549
Yeah, but it’s not amnesia.
I remember everything up until my injury.

34
00:05:03.633 --> 00:05:06.344
I just can’t make new memories.
So I can’t remember talking to you.

35
00:05:06.427 --> 00:05:09.388
What did we talk about? Oh, Sammy Jankis.

36
00:05:09.472 --> 00:05:11.808
I guess I tell people about Sammy
to help them understand.

37
00:05:11.891 --> 00:05:14.644
Sammy’s story helps me
understand my own situation.

38
00:05:14.727 --> 00:05:19.857
Sammy wrote himself endless
amounts of notes, but he got mixed up.

39
00:05:20.650 --> 00:05:23.319
I have a more graceful
solution to the memory problem.

40
00:05:26.656 --> 00:05:29.116
I’m disciplined and organized.

41
00:05:29.200 --> 00:05:31.744
I use habit and routine
to make my life possible.

42
00:05:32.912 --> 00:05:35.163
Sammy had no drive, no reason to make it work.

43
00:05:36.624 --> 00:05:40.837
Me? Yeah, I got a reason.

44
00:05:43.522 --> 00:05:47.260
I met Sammy through work.
Insurance. I was an investigator.

45
00:05:47.343 --> 00:05:50.221
I’d investigate the claims
to see which ones were phony.

46
00:05:50.304 --> 00:05:52.390
I had to see through people’s bullshit.

47
00:05:52.473 --> 00:05:55.268
It was useful experience,
’cause now it’s my life.

48
00:05:55.351 --> 00:05:58.187
When I meet someone,
I don’t know if I’ve met them before.

49
00:05:58.730 --> 00:06:01.190
I have to look in their eyes
and try and figure them out.

50
00:06:01.274 --> 00:06:04.569
<i>My job taught me the best way to find out
what someone knew was just let them talk…</i>

51
00:06:04.652 --> 00:06:07.028
<i>and watch the eyes and the body language.</i>

52
00:06:07.113 --> 00:06:10.700
<i>If someone scratches their nose while they’re
talking, experts tell you it means they’re lying.</i>

53
00:06:10.783 --> 00:06:14.287
<i>It really means they’re nervous.
People get nervous for all sorts of reasons.</i>

54
00:06:14.370 --> 00:06:15.580
<i>It’s all about context.</i>

55
00:06:15.663 --> 00:06:17.540
Yeah, I was good.

56
00:06:17.623 --> 00:06:20.626
Sammy was my first real challenge.

57
00:06:22.670 --> 00:06:25.298
I’d just become an investigator
when I came across Sammy.

58
00:06:25.381 --> 00:06:29.093
Mr. Samuel R. Jankis. Strangest case ever.

59
00:06:29.177 --> 00:06:31.971
You know, the guy’s a 58-year-old
semiretired accountant.

60
00:06:32.054 --> 00:06:34.724
He and his wife had been in this car accident.
Nothing too serious.

61
00:06:34.807 --> 00:06:38.019
<i>But he’s acting funny.
He can’t get a handle on what’s going on.</i>

62
00:06:39.478 --> 00:06:42.273
<i>The doctors find some possible damage
to the hippocampus.</i>

63
00:06:42.356 --> 00:06:46.903
<i>Nothing conclusive, but Sammy can’t remember
anything for more than a couple of minutes.</i>

64
00:06:46.986 --> 00:06:49.739
<i>Can’t work, can’t do shit.
The medical bills pile up.</i>

65
00:06:49.822 --> 00:06:52.533
<i>His wife calls the insurance company,
and I get sent in.</i>

66
00:06:53.117 --> 00:06:57.495
<i>Now, this is my first big claims investigation,
so I really check into it.</i>

67
00:06:58.164 --> 00:07:02.792
<i>Sammy can think just fine,
but he can’t make any new memories.</i>

68
00:07:02.877 --> 00:07:05.213
<i>He could only remember things
for a couple of minutes.</i>

69
00:07:05.296 --> 00:07:07.006
– This is Mr. Shelby.
<i>– He’d watch TV…</i>

70
00:07:07.089 --> 00:07:09.425
<i>but anything longer than
a couple of minutes was too confusing.</i>

71
00:07:09.509 --> 00:07:13.346
<i>He couldn’t remember how it began.
He liked commercials. They were short.</i>

72
00:07:13.429 --> 00:07:15.515
Sammy. It’s time for my shot.

73
00:07:15.598 --> 00:07:18.476
<i>The crazy part was that this guy…</i>

74
00:07:18.559 --> 00:07:21.771
<i>who couldn’t even follow the plot
of</i> Green Acres <i>anymore…</i>

75
00:07:21.854 --> 00:07:23.940
<i>could do the most complicated things…</i>

76
00:07:25.024 --> 00:07:27.400
<i>as long as he learned them
before the accident…</i>

77
00:07:28.736 --> 00:07:30.987
<i>and as long as he kept his mind
on what he was doing.</i>

78
00:07:31.072 --> 00:07:32.822
Be gentle.

79
00:07:32.907 --> 00:07:37.203
<i>The doctors assure me there’s a real condition
called anterograde memory loss…</i>

80
00:07:37.286 --> 00:07:39.247
<i>or short-term memory loss.</i>

81
00:07:39.330 --> 00:07:41.331
<i>It’s rare, but legit.</i>

82
00:07:43.084 --> 00:07:45.085
<i>But every time I see him…</i>

83
00:07:45.920 --> 00:07:47.838
<i>I catch this look…</i>

84
00:07:47.922 --> 00:07:51.509
<i>this slight look of recognition.</i>

85
00:07:52.134 --> 00:07:54.428
<i>But he says he can’t remember me at all.</i>

86
00:07:54.512 --> 00:07:56.638
Sammy, it’s okay. I got it. I got it.

87
00:07:57.431 --> 00:07:59.557
– Hi, Mr. Shelby.
– Hi, Mrs. Jankis.

88
00:07:59.642 --> 00:08:03.604
<i>I can read people,
and I’m thinking: bad actor.</i>

89
00:08:04.313 --> 00:08:07.130
So now I’m suspicious, and I order more tests.

90
00:08:08.041 --> 00:08:10.153
Sammy couldn’t pick up any new skills at all.

91
00:08:10.987 --> 00:08:14.574
But I find something
in my research: conditioning.

92
00:08:14.657 --> 00:08:17.660
Sammy should still be able to learn
through repetition.

93
00:08:17.743 --> 00:08:21.163
It’s how you learn stuff like riding a bike.
You just get better through practice.

94
00:08:21.247 --> 00:08:23.748
It’s a completely different part of the brain
from the short-term memory.

95
00:08:23.833 --> 00:08:26.919
So I had the doctors test
Sammy’s response to conditioning.

96
00:08:27.003 --> 00:08:29.172
Just pick up any three objects.

97
00:08:29.255 --> 00:08:31.424
That’s a test?

98
00:08:31.507 --> 00:08:34.093
Where were you guys when I did my CPA?

99
00:08:35.178 --> 00:08:36.345
Sorry.

100
00:08:40.391 --> 00:08:42.143
Ow! What the fuck?

101
00:08:42.226 --> 00:08:45.438
– It’s a test, Sammy.
– Test this, you fucking quack.

102
00:08:46.772 --> 00:08:48.941
<i>Some of the objects were electrified.</i>

103
00:08:49.025 --> 00:08:51.401
<i>They’d give him a small shock.
They kept repeating the test…</i>

104
00:08:51.485 --> 00:08:53.446
always with the same objects electrified.

105
00:08:53.529 --> 00:08:57.116
The point was to see if Sammy could learn
to avoid the electrified objects…

106
00:08:57.200 --> 00:08:59.201
not by memory, but by instinct.

107
00:09:01.329 --> 00:09:03.248
They kept testing Sammy for months…

108
00:09:03.331 --> 00:09:06.126
always with the same objects
carrying the electrical charge.

109
00:09:07.460 --> 00:09:08.962
Ow! What the fuck?

110
00:09:09.045 --> 00:09:11.464
– It’s a test, Sammy.
– Test this, you fucking quack!

111
00:09:11.548 --> 00:09:14.259
Even with total short-term memory loss…

112
00:09:14.342 --> 00:09:17.095
<i>Sammy should have learned to instinctively stop
picking up the wrong objects.</i>

113
00:09:17.179 --> 00:09:21.224
<i>All the previous cases responded to conditioning.
Sammy didn’t respond at all.</i>

114
00:09:21.308 --> 00:09:24.895
<i>It was enough to suggest that his condition
was psychological, not physical.</i>

115
00:09:24.978 --> 00:09:28.440
We turned down his claim on the grounds
that he wasn’t covered for mental illness.

116
00:09:29.399 --> 00:09:32.235
His wife got stuck with the bills,
and I got a big promotion.

117
00:09:34.112 --> 00:09:37.616
Conditioning didn’t work for Sammy,
so he became helpless.

118
00:09:37.699 --> 00:09:39.618
But it works for me.

119
00:09:40.160 --> 00:09:42.078
I live the way Sammy couldn’t.

120
00:09:42.162 --> 00:09:44.581
Habit and routine make my life possible.

121
00:09:44.664 --> 00:09:47.584
Conditioning. Acting on instinct.

122
00:09:49.544 --> 00:09:52.589
Sammy’s wife was crippled
by the cost of supporting him…

123
00:09:52.672 --> 00:09:54.758
and fighting the company’s decision.

124
00:09:56.635 --> 00:09:58.929
But it wasn’t the money that got to her.

125
00:09:59.012 --> 00:10:02.015
<i>– I never said that Sammy was faking.</i>
– Listen. I have an idea.

126
00:10:02.099 --> 00:10:03.724
Sammy, I have an idea.

127
00:10:03.809 --> 00:10:06.478
<i>Just that his problem was mental, not physical.</i>

128
00:10:06.561 --> 00:10:09.815
I want you to have a pen in your pocket, okay?

129
00:10:09.898 --> 00:10:12.442
<i>– But she couldn’t understand.</i>
– You’re gonna have a pad in your pocket.

130
00:10:12.526 --> 00:10:14.527
– I did something wrong?
– You did something wrong!

131
00:10:14.611 --> 00:10:17.739
We’re gonna deal with it.
We’re gonna try harder.

132
00:10:17.823 --> 00:10:19.949
<i>She looks into his eyes
and sees the same person.</i>

133
00:10:20.033 --> 00:10:23.161
<i>If it’s not a physical problem,
he should just snap out of it.</i>

134
00:10:23.245 --> 00:10:24.955
– Ellen called!
– Ellen called?

135
00:10:26.123 --> 00:10:29.668
– Ellen can’t come today! Ellen can’t come!
– Okay. I’m sorry!

136
00:10:29.751 --> 00:10:32.879
– I’m sorry. I’m trying. I’m sorry.
– Try harder!

137
00:10:36.633 --> 00:10:40.761
So good old Leonard Shelby from the insurance
company gives her the seed of doubt…

138
00:10:41.346 --> 00:10:43.472
just like he gave it to the doctors.

139
00:10:44.266 --> 00:10:46.977
But I never said that he was faking.
I never said that.

140
00:10:52.566 --> 00:10:56.236
What Mrs. Jankis didn’t understand was
that you can’t bully someone into remembering.

141
00:10:56.320 --> 00:10:58.321
The more pressure you’re under,
the harder it gets.

142
00:11:01.074 --> 00:11:03.075
Then call me back?

143
00:11:42.533 --> 00:11:44.243
Who is this?

144
00:11:46.161 --> 00:11:47.204
Yeah.

145
00:11:47.788 --> 00:11:48.997
Uh-huh.

146
00:11:50.832 --> 00:11:53.960
Sir, that’d certainly be in keeping
with some of my own discoveries.

147
00:11:54.544 --> 00:11:57.923
I was hoping for a little more on the drugs angle.
Can you hang on a sec?

148
00:12:06.515 --> 00:12:09.768
The police report mentioned
the drugs found in the car outside my house.

149
00:12:09.851 --> 00:12:11.937
The car was stolen,
but his prints were all over it.

150
00:12:12.020 --> 00:12:14.731
I got friends in the department.
They gave me a copy of it.

151
00:12:14.815 --> 00:12:17.109
I dealt with the police a lot
in my insurance job.

152
00:12:17.192 --> 00:12:21.278
With my condition, it’s really tough.
I can’t keep it all in mind at once.

153
00:12:21.363 --> 00:12:24.616
I have to summarize the different sections.
And there’s pages missing.

154
00:12:24.700 --> 00:12:26.868
I guess I’ve been trying to log them all.

155
00:12:26.952 --> 00:12:29.203
I don’t know why these are crossed out.

156
00:12:29.287 --> 00:12:31.206
But they weren’t even looking for John G.

157
00:12:31.289 --> 00:12:34.042
The stuff they found in the car fit in with
what they believed had happened…

158
00:12:34.126 --> 00:12:36.044
so they didn’t chase any of it up.

159
00:12:38.505 --> 00:12:41.550
There’s something about the drugs stashed
in the car that doesn’t ring true for me.

160
00:12:42.217 --> 00:12:44.136
Because the police claim
the guy was an addict…

161
00:12:44.219 --> 00:12:46.220
needing money to score,
which I think is bullshit…

162
00:12:46.304 --> 00:12:49.558
’cause he’s not gonna go breaking into places
while he’s still got a stash that big.

163
00:12:50.517 --> 00:12:53.186
I think John G. left it there
or planted it there.

164
00:12:55.021 --> 00:12:57.022
How do you know that?

165
00:12:58.483 --> 00:13:00.484
Shit. That’s true. It fits.

166
00:13:01.194 --> 00:13:03.155
So he’s a dealer.

167
00:13:03.822 --> 00:13:05.740
Hang on a sec.

168
00:13:15.876 --> 00:13:17.731
Now we’re getting somewhere.

169
00:13:19.295 --> 00:13:21.423
I can’t blame the cops
for not taking me seriously.

170
00:13:21.506 --> 00:13:23.842
This is a difficult condition
for people to understand.

171
00:13:23.925 --> 00:13:27.178
Look at Sammy Jankis.
His own wife couldn’t deal with it.

172
00:13:27.262 --> 00:13:29.806
I told you about how she tried
to get him to snap out of it.

173
00:13:29.889 --> 00:13:33.226
Eventually she came to see me at the office.
I found out all kinds of shit.

174
00:13:33.727 --> 00:13:36.187
<i>She told me about life with Sammy,
how she treated him.</i>

175
00:13:36.271 --> 00:13:37.730
Thank you for seeing me.

176
00:13:37.814 --> 00:13:40.567
It got to the point where she’d get Sammy
to hide food all around the house.

177
00:13:40.650 --> 00:13:42.402
Then she’d stop feeding him
to see if his hunger…

178
00:13:42.485 --> 00:13:44.446
would make him remember
where he’d hidden the food.

179
00:13:46.781 --> 00:13:49.409
<i>She wasn’t a cruel person.
She just wanted old Sammy back.</i>

180
00:13:49.492 --> 00:13:53.287
Mr. Shelby, you know all about Sammy
and you’ve decided that he’s faking.

181
00:13:53.371 --> 00:13:55.999
Mrs. Jankis, the company’s position
isn’t that Sammy is faking anything…

182
00:13:56.082 --> 00:13:58.001
just that his condition can’t be shown to be—

183
00:13:58.084 --> 00:14:01.546
I just want to know
what your honest opinion about Sammy is.

184
00:14:01.629 --> 00:14:04.549
We shouldn’t even be talking like this
while the case is still open to appeal.

185
00:14:04.632 --> 00:14:07.886
– I’m not appealing the decision.
– Then why are you here?

186
00:14:07.969 --> 00:14:10.430
Try to understand.
When I look at Sammy…

187
00:14:10.513 --> 00:14:13.975
I don’t see some… vegetable.

188
00:14:14.058 --> 00:14:16.144
I see my same old Sammy.

189
00:14:18.313 --> 00:14:22.734
What do you think that’s like for me to suspect
he might be imagining this whole problem…

190
00:14:22.817 --> 00:14:24.903
and that if I just could say the right thing…

191
00:14:24.986 --> 00:14:27.780
he’d snap out of it
and go back to being normal?

192
00:14:33.328 --> 00:14:37.123
If I knew that my old Sammy were truly gone…

193
00:14:37.207 --> 00:14:41.335
then I could say good-bye
and start loving this new Sammy.

194
00:14:43.338 --> 00:14:46.174
As long as I have doubt,
I can’t say good-bye and move on.

195
00:14:46.257 --> 00:14:48.009
What do you want from me?

196
00:14:48.092 --> 00:14:51.262
I want you to forget the company
you work for 30 seconds…

197
00:14:51.346 --> 00:14:55.016
and tell me if you really believe
that Sammy’s faking his condition.

198
00:14:56.184 --> 00:15:00.270
I need to know… what you honestly believe.

199
00:15:05.610 --> 00:15:09.197
I believe that Sammy should be physically
capable of making new memories.

200
00:15:17.121 --> 00:15:18.206
Thank you.

201
00:15:20.875 --> 00:15:23.795
I thought I helped her. I thought
she just needed some kind of answer.

202
00:15:23.878 --> 00:15:25.879
I didn’t think it was important
what the answer was…

203
00:15:26.714 --> 00:15:28.715
just that she had one to believe.

204
00:15:36.224 --> 00:15:39.143
No. She shouldn’t have
given me that responsibility.

205
00:15:39.227 --> 00:15:41.896
I’m a claims investigator, not a doctor.

206
00:15:43.189 --> 00:15:45.524
Yeah. I guess.

207
00:15:45.608 --> 00:15:47.984
But I’ve got all sorts of other considerations.

208
00:15:48.778 --> 00:15:51.279
Legal responsibility, large financial—

209
00:15:56.077 --> 00:15:57.745
Who is this?

210
00:16:25.606 --> 00:16:26.731
Front desk?

211
00:16:26.815 --> 00:16:29.401
Burt. Right.
This is Mr. Shelby in room 21.

212
00:16:30.236 --> 00:16:32.571
Yeah, that’s the thing. I don’t want any calls.

213
00:16:32.655 --> 00:16:34.635
Nope. None at all.

214
00:16:44.917 --> 00:16:45.960
Hello?

215
00:16:49.630 --> 00:16:51.799
It’s Burt, from the front desk.

216
00:16:54.093 --> 00:16:56.471
– Yeah?
– I know you said you didn’t want any calls.

217
00:16:56.554 --> 00:16:59.098
But this guy called.
He’s on the phone now. He says he’s a cop.

218
00:16:59.182 --> 00:17:00.641
– A cop?
– Yeah.

219
00:17:00.725 --> 00:17:04.270
He says you’re really gonna wanna
know what he has to say.

220
00:17:04.353 --> 00:17:07.940
I’m not too good on the phone. I need to look
people in the eye when I talk to them.

221
00:17:59.743 --> 00:18:01.787
Why are you calling me? What do you want?

222
00:18:02.538 --> 00:18:05.332
I know you’re a cop, but what do you want?
Have I done something wrong?

223
00:18:06.250 --> 00:18:08.376
I don’t know. Something bad, maybe.

224
00:18:10.963 --> 00:18:14.842
Why are you asking me? I can’t remember
what I’ve done. You wouldn’t believe me anyway.

225
00:18:14.925 --> 00:18:17.845
Because of my condition.
You don’t believe someone with this condition.

226
00:18:17.928 --> 00:18:20.824
Nobody believed Sammy!
I didn’t even fucking believe Sammy!

227
00:18:22.224 --> 00:18:24.600
It’s completely fucked
because nobody believes you.

228
00:18:25.811 --> 00:18:29.064
It’s amazing what a little brain damage
will do for your credibility.

229
00:18:29.147 --> 00:18:31.942
I guess it’s some kind of poetic justice
for not believing Sammy.

230
00:18:32.025 --> 00:18:34.194
You know the truth about my condition, Officer?

231
00:18:35.028 --> 00:18:37.029
You don’t know anything.

232
00:18:37.114 --> 00:18:39.283
You feel angry, you don’t know why.

233
00:18:39.366 --> 00:18:42.119
You feel guilty, you have no idea why.

234
00:18:42.953 --> 00:18:45.581
You could do anything and not have
the faintest idea 10 minutes later.

235
00:18:45.664 --> 00:18:48.040
Like Sammy.
What if I’ve done something like Sammy?

236
00:18:48.750 --> 00:18:52.004
I didn’t tell you what happened
to Sammy and his wife?

237
00:18:53.755 --> 00:18:56.925
She came to see me at my office. I thought
she was trying to catch me off guard…

238
00:18:57.009 --> 00:18:59.928
<i>so I didn’t tell her what I really thought,
but I never said that he was faking…</i>

239
00:19:00.012 --> 00:19:01.930
<i>just that his condition was mental,
not physical.</i>

240
00:19:02.014 --> 00:19:04.975
<i>I found out later that she went home
and gave Sammy his final exam.</i>

241
00:19:06.685 --> 00:19:09.646
Sammy? It’s time for my shot.

242
00:19:25.620 --> 00:19:27.621
<i>She knew beyond a doubt that he loved her.</i>

243
00:19:28.790 --> 00:19:30.751
<i>So she found a way to test him.</i>

244
00:19:43.472 --> 00:19:47.059
Sammy. It’s time for my shot.

245
00:19:57.027 --> 00:19:59.071
<i>She really thought she’d call his bluff.</i>

246
00:19:59.154 --> 00:20:00.654
There you go.

247
00:20:01.239 --> 00:20:05.077
<i>Or she just didn’t wanna live
with the things she’d put him through.</i>

248
00:20:15.045 --> 00:20:16.045
Sammy.

249
00:20:18.215 --> 00:20:20.341
It’s time for my shot.

250
00:20:25.806 --> 00:20:27.599
It won’t hurt.

251
00:21:11.727 --> 00:21:13.770
<i>She went into a coma and never recovered.</i>

252
00:21:14.938 --> 00:21:18.024
<i>Sammy couldn’t understand
or explain what happened.</i>

253
00:21:20.318 --> 00:21:22.237
He’s been in a home ever since.

254
00:21:22.320 --> 00:21:24.739
<i>He doesn’t even know that his wife is dead.</i>

255
00:21:24.823 --> 00:21:28.201
I was wrong about Sammy,
and I was wrong about his wife.

256
00:21:28.285 --> 00:21:30.203
She wasn’t interested in the money.

257
00:21:30.287 --> 00:21:32.456
She just needed to understand his problem.

258
00:21:32.539 --> 00:21:35.959
<i>His brain didn’t respond to conditioning.
But he wasn’t a con man.</i>

259
00:21:36.042 --> 00:21:39.462
<i>When she looked into his eyes,
she thought he could be the same person.</i>

260
00:21:39.546 --> 00:21:41.922
<i>When I looked into his eyes,
I thought I saw recognition.</i>

261
00:21:42.007 --> 00:21:44.133
Now I know. You fake it.

262
00:21:44.217 --> 00:21:47.053
If you think you’re supposed to
recognize somebody, you just pretend to.

263
00:21:47.137 --> 00:21:49.806
<i>You bluff it to get a pat
on the head from the doctors.</i>

264
00:21:50.432 --> 00:21:52.683
You bluff it to seem less of a freak.

265
00:21:56.313 --> 00:21:57.958
What drug dealer?

266
00:21:59.566 --> 00:22:02.819
So this Jimmy Grants deals drugs out of the bar
where his girlfriend works?

267
00:22:03.653 --> 00:22:06.156
But he’s not gonna bring her along.
He’ll come by himself, right?

268
00:22:07.490 --> 00:22:10.451
I always figured the drugs angle
would be the best way to get him.

269
00:22:11.494 --> 00:22:14.664
No, Officer. I’m as ready as I’ll ever be.

270
00:22:15.373 --> 00:22:17.917
You’re in the lobby? What do you look like?

271
00:22:19.210 --> 00:22:21.171
I’ll be right there.

272
00:23:03.296 --> 00:23:04.214
Lenny.

273
00:23:07.342 --> 00:23:08.551
Officer Gammell.

274
00:23:11.095 --> 00:23:13.806
Yeah. Come on.

275
00:23:30.323 --> 00:23:32.784
– Smile.
– Not here.

276
00:23:34.118 --> 00:23:35.411
Over here.

277
00:23:41.084 --> 00:23:44.087
– Is it Officer or Lieutenant Gammell?
– You know what?

278
00:23:44.170 --> 00:23:46.381
Don’t write Gammell, just Teddy.

279
00:23:47.048 --> 00:23:49.092
– Why?
– I’m undercover.

280
00:23:51.928 --> 00:23:54.347
This is the directions where he’s going.

281
00:23:54.430 --> 00:23:57.475
– My number’s on the bottom if you need me.
– You’re not coming?

282
00:23:57.559 --> 00:23:59.477
No. It wouldn’t be appropriate.

283
00:24:04.023 --> 00:24:07.110
Nice picture. I look thin.

284
00:24:10.822 --> 00:24:12.115
Hey, Lenny.

285
00:24:12.782 --> 00:24:14.200
Make him beg.

286
00:25:37.283 --> 00:25:38.533
Teddy!

287
00:25:41.746 --> 00:25:43.246
Hey, Teddy!

288
00:25:50.213 --> 00:25:51.381
Jimmy.

289
00:25:53.174 --> 00:25:55.760
– What the fuck are you doing here?
– You Jimmy Grants?

290
00:25:55.843 --> 00:25:57.844
Expecting any other Jimmys out here,
Memory Man?

291
00:25:57.929 --> 00:26:02.182
– Do you remember me?
– Yeah, I remember you.

292
00:26:02.266 --> 00:26:04.685
Where the fuck’s Teddy?

293
00:26:04.769 --> 00:26:05.478
Well?

294
00:26:09.607 --> 00:26:12.402
Motherfuck— Fuckin’ retard!

295
00:26:14.529 --> 00:26:17.573
– Strip.
– You’re making a big fucking mistake, pal.

296
00:26:17.657 --> 00:26:18.950
Strip!

297
00:26:21.035 --> 00:26:23.621
My associates are not
the kind of people you wanna piss off.

298
00:26:23.704 --> 00:26:25.289
Don’t say anything else.

299
00:26:25.373 --> 00:26:27.792
– I knew I couldn’t trust that fuck!
– Take it off.

300
00:26:30.420 --> 00:26:31.963
Cocksucker.

301
00:26:33.047 --> 00:26:34.841
Your pants too.

302
00:26:35.800 --> 00:26:37.760
– Why?
– I don’t wanna get blood on them.

303
00:26:39.846 --> 00:26:41.847
Wait. Did he tell you what I was bringing?

304
00:26:41.931 --> 00:26:45.851
– Take your fuckin’ pants off!
– I’ve got 200 grand stashed in the car!

305
00:26:45.935 --> 00:26:48.646
– Just take it!
– You think you can bargain with me?

306
00:26:48.730 --> 00:26:51.106
– Take the money and walk away!
– I don’t want your fuckin’ money.

307
00:26:52.150 --> 00:26:53.609
Then what?

308
00:26:54.152 --> 00:26:57.822
– What do you want from me?
– I want my fuckin’ life back!

309
00:28:28.412 --> 00:28:29.622
Sammy.

310
00:28:36.420 --> 00:28:38.464
He said “Sammy.”
How does he know about Sammy?

311
00:28:38.548 --> 00:28:39.923
Oh, fuck.

312
00:29:00.528 --> 00:29:02.529
What have I done?

313
00:29:04.407 --> 00:29:07.118
Mister, I need help.
There’s a guy in here, he’s hurt bad.

314
00:29:07.201 --> 00:29:09.452
– We gotta get him to a doctor.
– All right.

315
00:29:11.247 --> 00:29:13.541
I don’t know what happened.
I’ve got this memory thing.

316
00:29:13.624 --> 00:29:15.835
– Do I know you?
– No. Don’t worry. I’m a cop.

317
00:29:16.669 --> 00:29:19.463
– Is he still breathing?
– I don’t know. Maybe.

318
00:29:19.547 --> 00:29:22.091
What the hell were you guys
doing down here?

319
00:29:23.634 --> 00:29:25.720
I don’t remember. I have this condition.

320
00:29:25.803 --> 00:29:28.514
I hope it’s not as serious as his,
’cause this guy’s dead.

321
00:29:28.598 --> 00:29:31.142
Ow! Lenny! That shit kills!

322
00:29:31.225 --> 00:29:34.770
So you remember me now, huh?
You are a fuckin’ cop.

323
00:29:34.854 --> 00:29:37.690
Yeah. And I’m the guy
that helped you find him.

324
00:29:37.773 --> 00:29:39.650
Get up. Get up.

325
00:29:39.734 --> 00:29:41.777
Lenny, you got the wrong idea.

326
00:29:44.488 --> 00:29:46.532
Who is that? He knew me.

327
00:29:46.616 --> 00:29:49.242
Of course he did. He raped your wife.
He fucked up your brain.

328
00:29:49.327 --> 00:29:51.370
Bullshit. He’s not the guy.

329
00:29:51.454 --> 00:29:55.791
His name is James F. Grants.
John G. Check your tattoos.

330
00:29:55.875 --> 00:29:58.294
– What was he bringing the 200 grand for?
– What?

331
00:29:59.879 --> 00:30:02.673
– What was it for?
– A load of amphetamines I told him I had.

332
00:30:02.757 --> 00:30:06.218
– Is this a drug deal?
– No. Yeah, that and your thing.

333
00:30:06.302 --> 00:30:09.930
Look, Leonard, Jimmy’s your guy. I just
figured we’d make a few dollars on the side.

334
00:30:10.014 --> 00:30:13.643
– How did he know me?
– The Discount Inn. He dealt out of there.

335
00:30:13.726 --> 00:30:17.021
The guy at the front desk let him know
if anybody came snooping around.

336
00:30:17.104 --> 00:30:19.649
He called Jimmy the minute he saw you
taking a picture of the dump.

337
00:30:19.732 --> 00:30:22.108
– You’re fucking using me.
– No! You get half!

338
00:30:22.193 --> 00:30:24.819
He knew about Sammy!
Why would I tell him about fuckin’ Sammy?

339
00:30:24.904 --> 00:30:28.282
You tell everybody about Sammy,
everybody who’ll listen.

340
00:30:28.366 --> 00:30:30.492
“Remember Sammy Jankis?”
“Remember Sammy Jankis?”

341
00:30:30.576 --> 00:30:33.496
Great story.
Gets better every time you tell it.

342
00:30:34.455 --> 00:30:36.374
So you lie to yourself to be happy.

343
00:30:36.457 --> 00:30:38.501
There’s nothing wrong with that.
We all do it.

344
00:30:38.584 --> 00:30:41.712
Who cares if there’s a few little details
you’d rather not remember?

345
00:30:44.173 --> 00:30:46.509
– What the fuck are you talking about?
– I don’t know.

346
00:30:47.301 --> 00:30:49.220
Your wife surviving the assault.

347
00:30:50.012 --> 00:30:51.931
Her not believing your condition.

348
00:30:52.014 --> 00:30:56.185
The torment and pain and anguish
tearing her up inside.

349
00:30:56.769 --> 00:30:58.062
The insulin.

350
00:30:59.355 --> 00:31:02.066
That’s Sammy, not me.
I told you about Sammy.

351
00:31:02.149 --> 00:31:05.152
Yeah, right.
Like you tell yourself over and over again.

352
00:31:05.236 --> 00:31:07.237
Conditioning yourself to remember.

353
00:31:07.321 --> 00:31:09.907
– Learning through repetition.
– Sammy let his wife kill herself.

354
00:31:09.990 --> 00:31:15.037
– Sammy ended up in an institution.
– Sammy was a con man, a faker.

355
00:31:15.121 --> 00:31:17.289
I never said that Sammy was faking.

356
00:31:17.873 --> 00:31:20.334
You exposed him for what he was— a fraud.

357
00:31:20.418 --> 00:31:22.378
But I was wrong. That’s the whole point.

358
00:31:24.046 --> 00:31:26.799
– See, Sammy’s wife came to me.
– Sammy didn’t have a wife.

359
00:31:29.552 --> 00:31:31.887
It was <i>your</i> wife who had diabetes.

360
00:31:38.269 --> 00:31:39.269
Ouch.

361
00:31:41.897 --> 00:31:43.566
My wife wasn’t diabetic.

362
00:31:44.567 --> 00:31:45.985
You sure?

363
00:31:50.781 --> 00:31:53.909
– Ouch. Cut it out.
– She wasn’t diabetic.

364
00:31:54.910 --> 00:31:58.705
You think I don’t know my own wife?
What the fuck is wrong with you?

365
00:31:58.789 --> 00:32:02.209
I guess I can only make you remember
the things you wanna be true.

366
00:32:02.293 --> 00:32:04.669
– Like old Jimmy down there.
– He’s not the right guy.

367
00:32:04.754 --> 00:32:06.922
He was to you.

368
00:32:07.006 --> 00:32:10.426
Come on. You got your revenge.
Enjoy it while you still remember.

369
00:32:10.509 --> 00:32:13.012
What difference does it make
whether he was your guy or not?

370
00:32:13.095 --> 00:32:15.723
– It makes all the difference.
– Why? You’re never gonna know.

371
00:32:15.806 --> 00:32:17.099
– Yes, I will.
– No, you won’t.

372
00:32:17.183 --> 00:32:18.642
I will. Somehow I’ll know.

373
00:32:18.726 --> 00:32:21.145
– You won’t remember!
– When it’s done, I will know. It’ll be different.

374
00:32:21.228 --> 00:32:25.148
I thought so too.
In fact, I was sure of it, but you didn’t!

375
00:32:27.943 --> 00:32:31.197
That’s right. The real John G.

376
00:32:31.280 --> 00:32:34.867
I helped you find him over a year ago.
He’s already dead.

377
00:32:34.950 --> 00:32:37.828
– Don’t lie to me anymore.
– Look, Lenny.

378
00:32:38.454 --> 00:32:41.332
I was the cop assigned to your wife’s case.
I believed you.

379
00:32:41.415 --> 00:32:43.959
I thought you deserved a chance for revenge.

380
00:32:44.043 --> 00:32:47.338
I’m the one that helped you find the other guy
in your bathroom that night…

381
00:32:47.421 --> 00:32:49.757
the guy that cracked your skull
and fucked your wife.

382
00:32:49.840 --> 00:32:52.301
We found him. You killed him.

383
00:32:53.969 --> 00:32:59.308
But you didn’t remember.
So I helped you start looking again…

384
00:32:59.391 --> 00:33:01.644
looking for the guy you already killed.

385
00:33:02.186 --> 00:33:03.938
Yeah? So who was he?

386
00:33:04.021 --> 00:33:06.397
Just some guy. Does it even matter who?

387
00:33:07.149 --> 00:33:11.028
No reason, Lenny. No conspiracy.
Just bad fucking luck.

388
00:33:12.238 --> 00:33:15.991
Couple of junkies too strung out
to realize your wife didn’t live alone.

389
00:33:17.159 --> 00:33:20.954
But when you killed him,
I was so convinced that you’d remember.

390
00:33:21.539 --> 00:33:23.499
But it didn’t stick.

391
00:33:23.582 --> 00:33:26.335
Like nothing ever sticks.
Like this won’t stick.

392
00:33:31.006 --> 00:33:35.636
I took that picture… just when you did it.

393
00:33:37.638 --> 00:33:39.557
Look how happy you are.

394
00:33:40.891 --> 00:33:42.643
I wanted to see that face again.

395
00:33:42.726 --> 00:33:45.521
– Gee, thanks.
– Fuck you.

396
00:33:45.604 --> 00:33:49.358
I gave you a reason to live,
and you were more than happy to help.

397
00:33:49.441 --> 00:33:53.612
You don’t want the truth.
You make up your own truth.

398
00:33:53.696 --> 00:33:55.656
Like your police file.

399
00:33:56.490 --> 00:33:59.493
It was complete when I gave it to you.
Who took out the 12 pages?

400
00:33:59.577 --> 00:34:02.121
– You, probably.
– No, it wasn’t me. See, it was you.

401
00:34:02.204 --> 00:34:05.916
– Why would I do that?
– To create a puzzle you could never solve.

402
00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:07.918
You know how many towns?

403
00:34:08.002 --> 00:34:10.171
How many John G.’s or James G.’s?

404
00:34:10.254 --> 00:34:12.298
Shit, Lenny. I’m a fucking John G.

405
00:34:12.381 --> 00:34:15.634
– Your name is Teddy.
– My mother calls me Teddy.

406
00:34:15.718 --> 00:34:18.596
My name’s John Edward Gammell.

407
00:34:18.679 --> 00:34:19.722
Cheer up.

408
00:34:19.805 --> 00:34:22.558
There’s plenty of John G.’s for us to find.

409
00:34:25.936 --> 00:34:28.355
All you do is moan.

410
00:34:28.439 --> 00:34:30.774
I’m the one that has to live
with what you’ve done.

411
00:34:30.858 --> 00:34:32.568
I’m the one that put it all together.

412
00:34:32.651 --> 00:34:37.323
You wander around, you’re playing detective.
You’re living a dream, kid.

413
00:34:37.406 --> 00:34:41.492
A dead wife to pine for.
A sense of purpose to your life.

414
00:34:41.577 --> 00:34:44.914
A romantic quest that you wouldn’t end
even if I wasn’t in the picture.

415
00:34:46.207 --> 00:34:49.376
– I should kill you.
– Quit it. Lenny, come on.

416
00:34:49.460 --> 00:34:52.463
You’re not a killer.
That’s why you’re so good at it.

417
00:34:56.008 --> 00:34:58.761
What are you doing?
You know what time it is?

418
00:34:58.844 --> 00:35:00.930
It’s beer o’clock. I’m buying.

419
00:35:02.932 --> 00:35:04.057
Fuck.

420
00:35:14.151 --> 00:35:15.276
I’m not a killer.

421
00:35:16.570 --> 00:35:19.114
I’m just someone who wanted
to make things right.

422
00:35:25.162 --> 00:35:27.538
Can I just let myself forget
what you’ve told me?

423
00:35:44.765 --> 00:35:48.143
Can I just let myself forget
what you made me do?

424
00:36:02.408 --> 00:36:04.158
You think I just want another puzzle to solve?

425
00:36:04.994 --> 00:36:07.162
Another John G. to look for?

426
00:36:08.372 --> 00:36:10.249
You’re a John G.

427
00:36:11.959 --> 00:36:14.044
So you can be my John G.

428
00:36:22.511 --> 00:36:24.637
Do I lie to myself to be happy?

429
00:36:25.931 --> 00:36:27.683
In your case, Teddy…

430
00:36:28.809 --> 00:36:30.728
yes, I will.

431
00:36:43.866 --> 00:36:45.951
Hey, that’s not your car!

432
00:36:46.035 --> 00:36:48.620
– It is now.
– Jesus Christ, you can’t take it!

433
00:36:48.704 --> 00:36:51.623
– Why not?
– Because the guy you just killed owns it!

434
00:36:51.707 --> 00:36:53.417
Somebody’ll recognize it!

435
00:36:54.877 --> 00:36:57.963
I think I’d rather be mistaken
for a dead guy than a killer.

436
00:36:58.922 --> 00:37:01.425
I might hang on to this for a while.

437
00:37:02.259 --> 00:37:03.552
Lenny.

438
00:37:05.596 --> 00:37:08.097
Will you help me find the keys?

439
00:37:08.182 --> 00:37:09.932
Help me find my keys.

440
00:37:32.206 --> 00:37:35.501
I have to believe in a world
outside my own mind.

441
00:37:35.584 --> 00:37:37.753
I have to believe that
my actions still have meaning…

442
00:37:37.836 --> 00:37:39.797
even if I can’t remember them.

443
00:37:41.965 --> 00:37:44.635
I have to believe
that when my eyes are closed…

444
00:37:44.718 --> 00:37:46.804
the world’s still here.

445
00:37:48.013 --> 00:37:50.432
Do I believe the world’s still here?

446
00:37:53.352 --> 00:37:54.937
Is it still out there?

