00:55:57.807 --> 00:55:59.557
He’ll probably find you.

682
00:55:59.642 --> 00:56:02.979
– What do you mean?
– I told him about your car.

683
00:56:03.771 --> 00:56:04.771
Why?

684
00:56:06.983 --> 00:56:10.111
He was beating the shit out of me.
I had to tell him something.

685
00:56:11.195 --> 00:56:12.947
Just write it all down.

686
00:56:28.087 --> 00:56:29.337
Be careful.

687
00:56:30.423 --> 00:56:32.341
I’ll be fine.

688
00:56:39.432 --> 00:56:42.246
– A car this nice you should lock.
– Who the fuck are you?

689
00:56:52.486 --> 00:56:55.322
– A car this nice you should lock.
– Who the fuck are you?

690
00:56:55.405 --> 00:56:57.741
– Teddy, your buddy.
– Prove it.

691
00:56:57.824 --> 00:57:01.453
Sammy. Remember Sammy?
You told me about Sammy!

692
00:57:02.996 --> 00:57:04.498
Geez!

693
00:57:04.581 --> 00:57:06.500
What the fuck are you doing in my car?

694
00:57:06.583 --> 00:57:08.709
What, your sense of humor went with the memory?

695
00:57:08.794 --> 00:57:11.755
– Do you even know why you’re here?
– Unfinished business.

696
00:57:11.838 --> 00:57:14.216
Lenny, let me inform you.

697
00:57:14.299 --> 00:57:16.677
Your business here is very much finished.

698
00:57:16.760 --> 00:57:19.763
– You’re still here because of Natalie.
– Who’s Natalie?

699
00:57:19.846 --> 00:57:22.975
Schmuck, whose house do you think
you just walked out of?

700
00:57:25.352 --> 00:57:28.772
That’s right. Take a look at your pictures.
I bet you got one of her.

701
00:57:30.691 --> 00:57:32.985
Nice shot, Leibovitz.

702
00:57:33.652 --> 00:57:36.822
You’ll wanna make a note.
You can’t trust her.

703
00:57:36.905 --> 00:57:38.282
Yeah? Why’s that?

704
00:57:38.365 --> 00:57:41.618
Because by now she’s taken
a look at this suit and the car…

705
00:57:41.702 --> 00:57:46.080
and she’s starting to figure out ways
of turning the situation to her advantage.

706
00:57:47.040 --> 00:57:49.501
She’s already got you staying
with her, for Christ’s sakes.

707
00:57:49.584 --> 00:57:53.171
You can’t go back in there.
Let me give you the name of a motel.

708
00:57:53.255 --> 00:57:57.134
– You’re lucky I ran into you. That broad’s bad news.
– What do you mean, “bad news”?

709
00:57:57.217 --> 00:57:59.511
She’s involved with drugs.

710
00:57:59.595 --> 00:58:01.888
Look. These. You see these?

711
00:58:01.972 --> 00:58:03.932
This is the bar where she works.

712
00:58:04.016 --> 00:58:06.059
Her boyfriend’s a drug dealer.

713
00:58:06.143 --> 00:58:08.769
She takes orders for him, arranges meets.

714
00:58:08.854 --> 00:58:11.732
He writes messages on the back of these.

715
00:58:11.815 --> 00:58:14.359
Then she slips him the answers
when she serves him his drinks.

716
00:58:14.443 --> 00:58:18.529
– Why should I care?
– Because when she gets jammed up…

717
00:58:18.613 --> 00:58:20.782
she’s gonna use you to protect herself.

718
00:58:20.866 --> 00:58:22.075
From who?

719
00:58:22.159 --> 00:58:24.910
Guys are gonna wanna know
what happened to her boyfriend.

720
00:58:24.995 --> 00:58:28.540
Guys are gonna come after her.
Somebody’s gotta pay, Lenny.

721
00:58:28.624 --> 00:58:31.668
Somebody always pays.
Maybe she’ll make it you.

722
00:58:31.752 --> 00:58:35.255
Oh, yeah?
Maybe she’ll make it you. Is that it?

723
00:58:35.339 --> 00:58:37.257
You worried that she’s gonna use me against you?

724
00:58:37.341 --> 00:58:39.342
– No.
– Why not?

725
00:58:40.052 --> 00:58:42.678
Because she doesn’t know who I am.

726
00:58:43.680 --> 00:58:46.224
– Why are you following me?
– Maybe I wanna help.

727
00:58:47.017 --> 00:58:50.228
She doesn’t know anything about
your investigation, okay, Einstein?

728
00:58:50.312 --> 00:58:52.981
So write this down.

729
00:58:53.065 --> 00:58:57.736
When she offers to help,
it’ll be for her own reasons.

730
00:58:57.819 --> 00:59:02.616
I’m not lying.
Take my pen. Write this down.

731
00:59:02.699 --> 00:59:04.868
Do not trust her.

732
00:59:12.292 --> 00:59:15.796
– There. You happy now?
– I won’t be happy until you leave town.

733
00:59:15.879 --> 00:59:17.798
Why not?

734
00:59:17.881 --> 00:59:21.385
You ever wonder how long you can hang around
here before people start asking questions?

735
00:59:21.468 --> 00:59:22.552
What sort of questions?

736
00:59:22.636 --> 00:59:24.762
The same sort of questions
you should be asking yourself.

737
00:59:24.846 --> 00:59:27.391
– Like what?
– Like, how did you get this suit, the car?

738
00:59:27.474 --> 00:59:29.101
– I have money.
– From what?

739
00:59:29.184 --> 00:59:32.562
My wife’s death. I used to work in insurance.
We were well covered.

740
00:59:34.648 --> 00:59:38.402
So in your grief you wandered
into a Jaguar dealership.

741
00:59:40.737 --> 00:59:42.906
You don’t have a clue, do you?

742
00:59:42.989 --> 00:59:45.534
– You don’t even know who you are.
– Yes, I do.

743
00:59:45.617 --> 00:59:49.371
I don’t have amnesia. I remember
everything right up until the incident.

744
00:59:49.454 --> 00:59:51.248
I am Leonard Shelby.
I am from San Francisco—

745
00:59:51.331 --> 00:59:55.961
That’s who you were.
You do not know who you are…

746
00:59:56.044 --> 00:59:59.964
what you’ve become since… the incident.

747
01:00:00.048 --> 01:00:02.592
You wander around playing detective.

748
01:00:02.676 --> 01:00:05.262
You don’t even know how long ago it was.

749
01:00:06.430 --> 01:00:11.058
Let me put it this way. Were you wearing
designer suits when you sold insurance?

750
01:00:11.143 --> 01:00:14.938
– I didn’t sell insurance. I investigated it.
– Right. You’re an investigator.

751
01:00:15.856 --> 01:00:20.484
– Maybe you should start investigating yourself.
– Thank you for the advice.

752
01:00:22.696 --> 01:00:25.282
Look, do me a favor. Don’t go back in there.

753
01:00:25.949 --> 01:00:28.075
Will you take the motel out of town?

754
01:00:31.663 --> 01:00:33.623
It’s been fun, Lenny.

755
01:00:40.630 --> 01:00:42.591
“Do not trust her.”

756
01:00:44.384 --> 01:00:46.385
“Don’t believe his lies.”

757
01:00:59.316 --> 01:01:01.526
Fuck it. I need my own place.

758
01:01:09.006 --> 01:01:10.494
“Discount Inn.”

759
01:02:04.464 --> 01:02:06.675
Yeah, okay. Blonde’s fine.

760
01:02:09.052 --> 01:02:11.178
That’s what they say.

761
01:02:11.263 --> 01:02:13.389
The Discount Inn. 304.

762
01:02:14.391 --> 01:02:15.434
Leonard.

763
01:02:16.852 --> 01:02:18.270
What then?

764
01:02:18.854 --> 01:02:21.565
We just go to bed.
You wait for me to fall asleep.

765
01:02:21.648 --> 01:02:23.734
You go into the bathroom and you slam the door.

766
01:02:23.817 --> 01:02:26.361
– Slam it?
– Yeah. Loud enough to wake me up.

767
01:02:26.445 --> 01:02:28.405
– And that’s it?
– That’s it.

768
01:02:31.200 --> 01:02:34.244
First I just need you to put
these things around the room.

769
01:02:37.289 --> 01:02:40.417
Just pretend they’re your things
and that this is your bedroom.

770
01:02:52.220 --> 01:02:57.100
– Should I wear it?
– No. Just like you took it off or something.

771
01:03:00.062 --> 01:03:02.481
I don’t want you to use it. I’m sorry.

772
01:03:04.191 --> 01:03:06.276
I just mean put them
around the room…

773
01:03:06.360 --> 01:03:08.946
as if they were your things.

774
01:03:13.450 --> 01:03:15.451
Whatever gets you off.

775
01:04:14.845 --> 01:04:15.929
Honey.

776
01:04:18.432 --> 01:04:20.225
Honey, it’s late.

777
01:04:42.456 --> 01:04:44.374
Everything okay?

778
01:05:02.017 --> 01:05:03.477
You okay in there?

779
01:05:06.980 --> 01:05:08.690
Was it good for you?

780
01:05:10.901 --> 01:05:13.820
What? Was I supposed to lock the door?

781
01:05:14.738 --> 01:05:15.822
No.

782
01:05:18.241 --> 01:05:20.160
I’d like you to leave now.

783
01:06:58.215 --> 01:07:00.134
Ouch. Cut it out.

784
01:07:31.916 --> 01:07:35.085
– How can you read that again?
– It’s good.

785
01:07:36.337 --> 01:07:38.214
Yeah, but you’ve read it,
like, a thousand times.

786
01:07:38.297 --> 01:07:39.882
I enjoy it.

787
01:07:41.050 --> 01:07:43.886
I always thought the pleasure of a book
was in wanting to know what happens next.

788
01:07:43.969 --> 01:07:45.679
Don’t be a prick.

789
01:07:45.763 --> 01:07:48.349
I’m not reading it to annoy you. I enjoy it.

790
01:07:49.475 --> 01:07:51.976
Just let me read, please.

791
01:08:02.822 --> 01:08:05.198
Probably tried this before.

792
01:08:07.326 --> 01:08:10.162
Probably burned truckloads of your stuff.

793
01:08:12.706 --> 01:08:14.707
Can’t remember to forget you.

794
01:09:00.962 --> 01:09:02.589
Do I know this guy?

795
01:09:04.049 --> 01:09:05.592
He seems to know me.

796
01:09:10.430 --> 01:09:11.848
What the fuck?

797
01:09:25.445 --> 01:09:27.614
– I like your car.
– Thank you.

798
01:09:27.697 --> 01:09:29.698
– Where’d you get it?
– Are you interested in buying one?

799
01:09:30.325 --> 01:09:32.244
I haven’t made a strong enough
impression on you?

800
01:09:32.327 --> 01:09:34.328
I wouldn’t be too hard on yourself.

801
01:09:45.048 --> 01:09:46.967
Okay. What am I doing?

802
01:09:54.349 --> 01:09:56.142
Okay. What am I doing?

803
01:09:58.478 --> 01:10:00.105
I’m chasing this guy.

804
01:10:02.691 --> 01:10:05.360
No. He’s chasing me.

805
01:10:28.174 --> 01:10:29.801
Fuck.

806
01:10:33.221 --> 01:10:35.515
“Dodd. White guy.

807
01:10:35.599 --> 01:10:37.559
Mountcrest Inn on Fifth Street.”

808
01:10:38.518 --> 01:10:41.187
I’ll get the jump on you, you fucker.

809
01:11:17.724 --> 01:11:19.184
Fuck.

810
01:11:21.853 --> 01:11:23.188
Sorry.

811
01:11:56.721 --> 01:11:58.722
I need a weapon.

812
01:12:01.976 --> 01:12:03.144
This’ll do.

813
01:12:26.876 --> 01:12:29.233
I don’t feel drunk.

814
01:12:33.174 --> 01:12:35.552
I don’t feel drunk.

815
01:13:47.749 --> 01:13:49.249
– Hello?
– Shit.

816
01:13:49.334 --> 01:13:50.752
Housekeeping.

817
01:13:50.835 --> 01:13:52.921
– Not right now.
– I’m sorry.

818
01:14:16.236 --> 01:14:17.112
Okay.

819
01:14:21.825 --> 01:14:25.953
“Dodd. Put him onto Teddy
or just get rid of him for Natalie.”

820
01:14:32.001 --> 01:14:33.128
Dodd.

821
01:14:38.299 --> 01:14:41.678
Get rid of him. Ask Natalie.

822
01:14:43.930 --> 01:14:45.180
Teddy, Teddy.

823
01:14:56.609 --> 01:14:58.862
<i>Leave your number.
You know what to do.</i>

824
01:14:58.945 --> 01:15:01.114
Yeah. This is a message for Teddy.

825
01:15:01.197 --> 01:15:03.241
I’m at the Mountcrest Inn
of Fifth Street, room six.

826
01:15:03.324 --> 01:15:06.327
I need you to come over
as soon as you get this. It’s important.

827
01:15:06.411 --> 01:15:08.662
This is Leonard. Thanks. Bye.

828
01:15:12.959 --> 01:15:14.461
Fuck.

829
01:15:30.810 --> 01:15:32.060
Awake.

830
01:15:33.813 --> 01:15:35.313
Where am I?

831
01:15:36.982 --> 01:15:38.526
Motel room.

832
01:15:45.116 --> 01:15:47.660
Some anonymous motel room.

833
01:15:51.163 --> 01:15:54.583
Nothing in the drawers,
but I’ll take a look anyway.

834
01:15:55.251 --> 01:15:58.129
Nothing except the Gideon Bible.

835
01:16:12.768 --> 01:16:14.353
Lenny! Open up!

836
01:16:16.522 --> 01:16:18.149
Just a minute.

837
01:16:18.232 --> 01:16:19.775
Open the door.

838
01:16:22.027 --> 01:16:23.112
Lenny.

839
01:16:25.906 --> 01:16:27.867
Open the door.

840
01:16:31.620 --> 01:16:32.872
Come on!

841
01:16:34.749 --> 01:16:36.459
Hi, Teddy.

842
01:16:36.542 --> 01:16:38.793
Finished playing with yourself, Lenny?

843
01:16:50.973 --> 01:16:53.058
I get it.

844
01:16:53.142 --> 01:16:54.602
Amorous neighbors.

845
01:16:54.685 --> 01:16:56.145
What are you doing here?

846
01:16:56.937 --> 01:16:59.940
You called me. You said you needed my help.

847
01:17:00.024 --> 01:17:03.569
I’ve had more rewarding
friendships than this one.

848
01:17:03.652 --> 01:17:06.989
Although I do get to keep
telling the same jokes.

849
01:17:07.656 --> 01:17:09.742
What the fuck is that?

850
01:17:15.247 --> 01:17:17.248
– Who the fuck is that?
– You don’t know him?

851
01:17:17.333 --> 01:17:18.958
No! Should I?

852
01:17:19.043 --> 01:17:20.668
Wait a minute.

853
01:17:20.753 --> 01:17:23.214
– Is that John G.?
– I don’t think so.

854
01:17:23.297 --> 01:17:26.592
– You don’t think so? You didn’t write it down?
– I might’ve fallen asleep before I did.

855
01:17:26.675 --> 01:17:28.676
For Christ’s sakes!

856
01:17:29.970 --> 01:17:31.514
Ask him.

857
01:17:35.601 --> 01:17:37.144
What’s your name?

858
01:17:37.228 --> 01:17:38.228
Your name.

859
01:17:38.813 --> 01:17:40.648
– Dodd.
– Who did this to you?

860
01:17:40.731 --> 01:17:43.317
– What?
– Who did this to you?

861
01:17:43.400 --> 01:17:44.902
You did.

862
01:17:48.155 --> 01:17:51.408
– I’m not gonna help you kill that guy.
– No, just let me think for a minute.

863
01:17:57.206 --> 01:17:59.625
Okay, Natalie. Who’s Natalie?

864
01:17:59.708 --> 01:18:01.168
– Natalie who?
– Why?

865
01:18:01.252 --> 01:18:04.338
– Maybe I know her.
– Look. We gotta get him out of here.

866
01:18:05.256 --> 01:18:06.881
All right, all right.

867
01:18:08.008 --> 01:18:09.969
He’s gotta have a car, right?

868
01:18:10.052 --> 01:18:13.639
We take him down to his car, tell him to get
the fuck out of town or we’re gonna kill him.

869
01:18:13.722 --> 01:18:15.808
We can’t walk him out of here
tied up and bleeding.

870
01:18:15.891 --> 01:18:18.352
– How the fuck did you get him up here?
– I don’t know.

871
01:18:18.435 --> 01:18:20.396
You don’t know.

872
01:18:22.565 --> 01:18:24.483
Yes, I do. This is not my room.

873
01:18:24.567 --> 01:18:26.360
It must be his room. Great! Let’s go.

874
01:18:26.443 --> 01:18:28.404
– No, no. We can’t just leave him here.
– Why not?

875
01:18:28.487 --> 01:18:33.033
Because the maid’s gonna walk in.
She’ll see him, call the cops. He can ID us.

876
01:18:34.910 --> 01:18:36.745
Okay. We untie him…

877
01:18:36.829 --> 01:18:39.707
we clean him up, and we march him
out of here with a gun in his back.

878
01:18:39.790 --> 01:18:41.750
A gun. Why would I have a gun?

879
01:18:43.252 --> 01:18:46.589
It must be his. I don’t think
they’d let someone like me carry a gun.

880
01:18:48.132 --> 01:18:49.425
Fucking hope not.

881
01:18:56.765 --> 01:18:58.267
Which one?

882
01:19:01.270 --> 01:19:03.814
We should probably steal his car.
You know, teach him a lesson.

883
01:19:03.897 --> 01:19:04.857
Shut up.

884
01:19:04.940 --> 01:19:07.359
That’s all right for you to say.
You’re the one with the Jag.

885
01:19:07.443 --> 01:19:10.321
Get in.
I’m gonna ride with him. You follow us.

886
01:19:10.404 --> 01:19:12.323
Give me your keys.

887
01:19:12.406 --> 01:19:14.617
Take your own car.

888
01:19:42.561 --> 01:19:45.606
– So was he scared?
– Yeah. I think it was your sinister mustache.

889
01:19:45.689 --> 01:19:48.400
Fuck you. You should have stolen his car.

890
01:19:48.484 --> 01:19:51.528
– Why? What’s wrong with this one?
– Nothing. You want to trade?

891
01:19:54.865 --> 01:19:56.951
So what do you do now?

892
01:19:57.034 --> 01:19:59.495
I’m going to find out
what the fuck that was all about.

893
01:20:07.086 --> 01:20:09.505
Natalie, right? Who the fuck is Dodd?

894
01:20:32.526 --> 01:20:35.029
Natalie, right? Who the fuck is Dodd?

895
01:20:38.658 --> 01:20:41.744
– Guess I don’t have to worry about him anymore.
– What the fuck have you got me into?

896
01:20:41.827 --> 01:20:43.329
Come inside.

897
01:20:46.540 --> 01:20:49.502
– Who is he?
– Calm down. Okay?

898
01:20:49.585 --> 01:20:53.089
This is my problem. You offered to help.
It has nothing to do with your investigation.

899
01:20:53.172 --> 01:20:54.674
How did you get me into this?

900
01:20:54.757 --> 01:20:56.801
You offered to help when you saw
what he did to my face.

901
01:20:56.884 --> 01:21:00.471
– How do I know he did that to your face?
– Because I came straight to you after he did it.

902
01:21:00.554 --> 01:21:02.807
I showed you what he did,
and I asked you to help me.

903
01:21:02.890 --> 01:21:04.850
– And I just take your word?
– Yeah.

904
01:21:06.310 --> 01:21:08.229
Something doesn’t feel right.

905
01:21:08.312 --> 01:21:10.856
I think someone’s fucking with me,
trying to get me to kill the wrong guy.

906
01:21:10.940 --> 01:21:12.358
– Did you?
– What?

907
01:21:12.441 --> 01:21:14.860
– Kill him?
– Of course not!

908
01:21:14.944 --> 01:21:15.986
Hey.

909
01:21:16.070 --> 01:21:17.905
Sit down, okay? Sit.

910
01:21:18.739 --> 01:21:21.826
This has nothing to do with you.

911
01:21:21.909 --> 01:21:24.285
You helped me out, and I’m grateful.

912
01:21:25.246 --> 01:21:27.081
You have to burn them.

913
01:21:29.500 --> 01:21:32.670
Leonard, you decided to help me.
Trust yourself.

914
01:21:32.753 --> 01:21:34.754
Trust your own judgment.
You can question everything.

915
01:21:34.839 --> 01:21:38.592
– You can never know anything for sure.
– There are things you know for sure.

916
01:21:38.676 --> 01:21:39.801
Such as?

917
01:21:41.679 --> 01:21:44.098
I know what that’s gonna sound like
when I knock on it.

918
01:21:44.807 --> 01:21:47.183
I know what that’s gonna
feel like when I pick it up.

919
01:21:47.268 --> 01:21:50.938
See? Certainties. It’s the kind
of memory you take for granted.

920
01:21:52.440 --> 01:21:54.941
You know, I can remember so much.

921
01:21:56.944 --> 01:22:00.239
The feel of the world… and her.

922
01:22:07.121 --> 01:22:08.664
She’s gone.

923
01:22:08.748 --> 01:22:12.710
And the present is trivia,
which I scribble down as fucking notes!

924
01:22:12.793 --> 01:22:15.713
Hey. Come on. Try and relax. Come on.

925
01:22:15.796 --> 01:22:18.132
It’s not easy for me to relax, you know?

926
01:22:18.924 --> 01:22:20.885
Come on. Take your jacket off.

927
01:22:21.469 --> 01:22:23.512
Now. Come on.

928
01:22:25.473 --> 01:22:27.057
Hey.

929
01:22:28.767 --> 01:22:30.936
Didn’t think you were the type.

930
01:22:38.861 --> 01:22:39.986
It’s backwards.

931
01:22:41.697 --> 01:22:42.740
Come here.

932
01:22:43.324 --> 01:22:44.492
Come here.

933
01:23:06.305 --> 01:23:08.431
What about here?

934
01:23:09.683 --> 01:23:12.186
Maybe it’s for when I find him.

935
01:23:14.939 --> 01:23:17.358
I’ve lost somebody too.

936
01:23:19.360 --> 01:23:20.778
I’m sorry.

937
01:23:20.861 --> 01:23:23.072
His name was Jimmy.

938
01:23:23.155 --> 01:23:26.200
– What happened to him?
– He went to meet somebody.

939
01:23:26.283 --> 01:23:28.244
He never came back.

940
01:23:29.245 --> 01:23:31.996
– Who did he go to meet?
– A guy called Teddy.

941
01:23:33.290 --> 01:23:35.291
What do the police think?

942
01:23:35.376 --> 01:23:38.254
They don’t look too hard for guys like Jimmy.

943
01:23:39.922 --> 01:23:43.884
When you find this guy, this John G…

944
01:23:45.010 --> 01:23:46.929
what are you gonna do?

945
01:23:48.430 --> 01:23:50.599
I’m gonna kill him.

946
01:23:52.142 --> 01:23:54.186
Maybe I can help you find him.

947
01:23:59.191 --> 01:24:01.694
I don’t even know how long she’s been gone.

948
01:24:06.073 --> 01:24:09.076
It’s like I’ve woken up in bed
and she’s not here…

949
01:24:11.579 --> 01:24:13.955
because she’s gone to
the bathroom or something.

950
01:24:18.919 --> 01:24:21.005
But somehow I just—

951
01:24:21.755 --> 01:24:25.050
I just know she’s never gonna come back to bed.

952
01:24:30.598 --> 01:24:36.103
If I could just reach over
and touch her side of the bed…

953
01:24:37.771 --> 01:24:39.897
I would know that it was cold.

954
01:24:43.068 --> 01:24:45.029
But I can’t.

955
01:24:49.158 --> 01:24:50.951
I know I can’t have her back.

956
01:24:52.661 --> 01:24:56.664
But I don’t want to wake up
in the morning thinking she’s still here.

957
01:24:58.208 --> 01:25:02.588
I lie here not knowing
how long I’ve been alone.

958
01:25:11.138 --> 01:25:13.432
How can I heal?

959
01:25:15.893 --> 01:25:20.981
How am I supposed to heal
if I can’t… feel time?

960
01:26:33.846 --> 01:26:36.306
“She has also lost someone.

961
01:26:36.849 --> 01:26:38.850
She will help you out of pity.”

962
01:27:07.128 --> 01:27:08.503
Awake.

963
01:27:10.423 --> 01:27:12.216
Where am I?

964
01:27:16.095 --> 01:27:17.847
Somebody’s bedroom.

965
01:27:19.557 --> 01:27:21.517
It must be her room.

966
01:27:22.935 --> 01:27:24.645
But who is she?

967
01:27:32.903 --> 01:27:34.864
It’s only me.

968
01:27:37.116 --> 01:27:40.077
– Did you sleep okay?
– Yeah. You?

969
01:27:41.871 --> 01:27:45.541
Oh, shit. I gotta be someplace.

970
01:27:50.212 --> 01:27:53.049
– It’s pretty weird.
– It’s useful.

971
01:27:54.091 --> 01:27:56.052
You never write a phone number on your hand?

972
01:27:56.677 --> 01:28:01.599
I should be able to talk to my friend
today about the license plate.

973
01:28:01.682 --> 01:28:05.519
– Yeah, the license plate.
– John G.’s license plate.

974
01:28:08.731 --> 01:28:10.649
You have it tattooed on your thigh.

975
01:28:28.918 --> 01:28:30.503
“Natalie.”

976
01:28:33.089 --> 01:28:35.090
“She has also lost someone.

977
01:28:35.174 --> 01:28:37.093
She will help you out of pity.”

978
01:28:42.348 --> 01:28:44.266
If it’s registered in this state…

979
01:28:44.350 --> 01:28:47.353
it should only take a couple seconds
to pull up his license and registration.

980
01:28:47.436 --> 01:28:49.230
I’ll call you as soon as I talk to him.

981
01:28:49.313 --> 01:28:53.316
Do you think we could just arrange a meeting now?
I’m not too good on the phone.

982
01:29:01.909 --> 01:29:03.910
It’s great that you—

983
01:29:05.412 --> 01:29:09.500
that you’re helping me like this.

984
01:29:09.583 --> 01:29:13.087
I’m helping you because you helped me.

985
01:29:25.182 --> 01:29:29.061
So next time you see me,
will you remember me?

986
01:29:46.162 --> 01:29:48.080
I think you will.

987
01:29:49.832 --> 01:29:51.542
I’m sorry.

988
01:29:54.670 --> 01:29:57.506
Lenny, before you go,
could I have my shirt back, please?

989
01:30:12.813 --> 01:30:16.672
Yo, Lenny! I thought you split for good.

990
01:30:22.322 --> 01:30:25.283
Yo, Lenny! I thought you split for good.

991
01:30:25.367 --> 01:30:28.661
– Things change.
– So I see.

992
01:30:28.745 --> 01:30:31.831
– My name’s Teddy.
– I guess I’ve told you about my condition.

993
01:30:31.915 --> 01:30:35.918
Only every time I see you.
Come on, I’ll buy you lunch.

994
01:30:41.549 --> 01:30:43.802
– Have I told you about Sammy Jankis?
– Yeah.

995
01:30:43.885 --> 01:30:48.431
I’m sick of hearing about the guy.
What about John G.? You think he’s still here?

996
01:30:48.515 --> 01:30:50.766
– Who?
– Johnny G., the guy you’re looking for.

997
01:30:50.850 --> 01:30:53.436
– That’s why you haven’t left town, am I right?
– Maybe.

998
01:30:53.520 --> 01:30:56.815
– Leonard, look. You have to be very careful.
– Why?

999
01:30:56.898 --> 01:31:00.318
The other day you mentioned that maybe
somebody was trying to set you up…

1000
01:31:00.402 --> 01:31:02.152
get you to kill the wrong guy.

1001
01:31:02.237 --> 01:31:05.323
I go on facts, not recommendations,
but thank you.

1002
01:31:05.407 --> 01:31:08.451
Lenny, you can’t trust a man’s life
to your little notes and pictures.

1003
01:31:08.535 --> 01:31:11.329
– Why not?
– Because your notes could be unreliable.

1004
01:31:11.413 --> 01:31:13.081
– Memory’s unreliable.
– Oh, please!

1005
01:31:13.164 --> 01:31:15.500
No, really. Memory’s not perfect.
It’s not even that good.

1006
01:31:15.583 --> 01:31:19.128
Ask the police.
Eyewitness testimony is unreliable.

1007
01:31:19.212 --> 01:31:22.173
The cops don’t catch a killer
by sitting around remembering stuff.

1008
01:31:22.257 --> 01:31:25.051
They collect facts, they make notes,
and they draw conclusions.

1009
01:31:25.135 --> 01:31:27.178
Facts, not memories.

1010
01:31:27.262 --> 01:31:29.723
That’s how you investigate.
I know. It’s what I used to do.

1011
01:31:29.806 --> 01:31:34.018
Memory can change the shape of a room.
It can change the color of a car.

1012
01:31:34.102 --> 01:31:36.187
And memories can be distorted.

1013
01:31:36.271 --> 01:31:38.440
They’re just an interpretation.
They’re not a record.

1014
01:31:38.523 --> 01:31:40.608
They’re irrelevant if you have the facts.

1015
01:31:41.443 --> 01:31:43.403
You really want to get this guy, don’t you?

1016
01:31:43.486 --> 01:31:46.281
He killed my wife.
He took away my fucking memory.

1017
01:31:49.200 --> 01:31:51.201
He destroyed my ability to live.

1018
01:31:55.081 --> 01:31:56.124
You’re living.

1019
01:31:57.959 --> 01:31:59.919
Only for revenge.

1020
01:32:00.003 --> 01:32:02.839
Then we’ll get the bastard.
Where you staying?

1021
01:32:05.633 --> 01:32:07.385
The Discount Inn.

1022
01:32:09.012 --> 01:32:10.930
I don’t know what room.
I haven’t got my key.

1023
01:32:11.014 --> 01:32:12.849
Probably left it in your room.

1024
01:32:27.655 --> 01:32:30.408
Hi. I’m checked in here,
but I think I’ve misplaced my key.

1025
01:32:31.117 --> 01:32:34.746
How you doing, Leonard?
Probably in the room, right?

1026
01:32:53.431 --> 01:32:55.016
– Don’t see my key anywhere.
– Shit.

1027
01:32:55.099 --> 01:32:57.185
This is the wrong room.
You’re in 304 now.

1028
01:32:57.268 --> 01:32:59.269
– I’m sorry. I fucked up.
– This is not my room?

1029
01:32:59.354 --> 01:33:00.854
No. Let’s go.

1030
01:33:01.981 --> 01:33:03.942
Why is this my handwriting?

1031
01:33:08.071 --> 01:33:10.907
This was your room,
but now you’re in 304.

1032
01:33:10.990 --> 01:33:13.243
– When was I in here?
– Last week.

1033
01:33:13.326 --> 01:33:15.787
But then I rented you
another room on top of it.

1034
01:33:15.870 --> 01:33:17.996
– Why?
– Business is slow.

1035
01:33:18.081 --> 01:33:20.959
I told my boss
about your condition and stuff…

1036
01:33:21.042 --> 01:33:23.253
and he said,
“Try and rent him another room.”

1037
01:33:23.336 --> 01:33:25.380
How many rooms am I checked
into in this shit-hole?

1038
01:33:25.463 --> 01:33:27.924
Just two, so far.

1039
01:33:29.551 --> 01:33:31.677
At least you’re being honest
about ripping me off.

1040
01:33:31.761 --> 01:33:34.305
You’re not gonna remember anyway.

1041
01:33:34.389 --> 01:33:36.307
You don’t have to be that honest, Burt.

1042
01:33:36.391 --> 01:33:40.019
Leonard, always get a receipt.

1043
01:33:40.103 --> 01:33:42.313
Yeah. I’m gonna write that down.

1044
01:33:44.774 --> 01:33:46.860
– What time is it?
– Quarter to 1:00.

1045
01:33:50.488 --> 01:33:51.613
Your room’s—

1046
01:34:04.419 --> 01:34:06.401
– Natalie?
– You don’t remember me.

1047
01:34:23.395 --> 01:34:26.565
“Today, 1:00 p.m. Meet Natalie for info.

1048
01:34:27.524 --> 01:34:29.234
She has also lost someone.

1049
01:34:29.318 --> 01:34:32.738
She will help you out of pity.”

1050
01:34:48.962 --> 01:34:51.465
– Natalie?
– You don’t remember me.

1051
01:34:51.548 --> 01:34:55.468
– Sorry. I should have explained. I have this—
– You did explain, Lenny.

1052
01:34:55.552 --> 01:34:57.928
Please call me Leonard.
My wife called me Lenny.

1053
01:34:58.013 --> 01:35:01.600
– Yeah, I know. You told me.
– Then I probably told you how much I hated it.

1054
01:35:01.683 --> 01:35:03.101
Yeah.

1055
01:35:04.186 --> 01:35:06.605
Do you mind taking your glasses off?
It’s hard for me to—

1056
01:35:08.190 --> 01:35:11.652
Thanks. So you have information for me?

1057
01:35:11.735 --> 01:35:14.488
– Is that what your little note says?
– Yeah.

1058
01:35:14.571 --> 01:35:17.449
Must be tough living your life
according to a couple of scraps of paper.

1059
01:35:17.532 --> 01:35:19.326
You mix your laundry list
with your grocery list…

1060
01:35:19.409 --> 01:35:21.578
and you’ll end up
eating your underwear for breakfast.

1061
01:35:22.621 --> 01:35:25.415
I guess that’s why you have
those freaky tattoos.

1062
01:35:26.541 --> 01:35:29.669
Yeah, it’s tough. It’s almost impossible.

1063
01:35:30.212 --> 01:35:32.713
I’m sorry I don’t remember you.
It’s nothing personal.

1064
01:35:35.842 --> 01:35:37.968
I do have information for you.

1065
01:35:38.637 --> 01:35:40.638
You gave me a license plate number.

1066
01:35:41.848 --> 01:35:43.934
Had my friend at DMV trace it.

1067
01:35:44.768 --> 01:35:46.478
Guess what name came up.

1068
01:35:47.813 --> 01:35:51.066
John Edward Gammell. John G.

1069
01:35:51.149 --> 01:35:53.777
– Do you know him?
– No.

1070
01:35:53.860 --> 01:35:56.947
But his face on his driver’s license
looked really familiar.

1071
01:35:57.030 --> 01:35:59.031
I think he’s been in the bar, maybe.

1072
01:35:59.116 --> 01:36:02.119
Here’s a copy of his license,
his registration, photo and all.

1073
01:36:02.786 --> 01:36:04.705
Are you sure you want this?

1074
01:36:04.788 --> 01:36:07.582
– Have I told you what this man did?
– Yeah.

1075
01:36:07.666 --> 01:36:09.418
Then you shouldn’t have to ask.

1076
01:36:09.501 --> 01:36:12.212
But even if you get revenge,
you’re not gonna remember it.

1077
01:36:12.295 --> 01:36:14.381
You’re not even gonna know that it happened.

1078
01:36:14.464 --> 01:36:17.801
My wife deserves vengeance. Doesn’t make
any difference whether I know about it.

1079
01:36:17.884 --> 01:36:22.139
Just because there are things I don’t remember
doesn’t make my actions meaningless.

1080
01:36:22.222 --> 01:36:25.183
The world doesn’t just disappear
when you close your eyes, does it?

1081
01:36:26.351 --> 01:36:29.896
Anyway, maybe I’ll take
a photograph to remind myself…

1082
01:36:29.980 --> 01:36:32.149
get another freaky tattoo.

1083
01:36:36.611 --> 01:36:38.530
Tell me about her again.

1084
01:36:39.990 --> 01:36:41.115
Why?

1085
01:36:41.199 --> 01:36:43.118
Because you like to remember her.

1086
01:36:45.871 --> 01:36:47.789
She was beautiful.

1087
01:36:49.666 --> 01:36:54.421
– To me, she was perfect.
– No. Don’t just recite the words.

1088
01:36:55.714 --> 01:36:59.468
Close your eyes… and remember her.

1089
01:37:10.520 --> 01:37:13.148
You can just feel the details.

1090
01:37:15.066 --> 01:37:17.861
The bits and pieces
you never bothered to put into words.

1091
01:37:22.532 --> 01:37:25.368
And you can feel these extreme moments…

1092
01:37:25.452 --> 01:37:27.370
<i>even if you don’t want to.</i>

1093
01:37:30.040 --> 01:37:33.043
<i>You put these together,
and you get the feel of a person.</i>

1094
01:37:36.546 --> 01:37:38.547
Enough to know how much you miss them…

1095
01:37:44.346 --> 01:37:47.057
<i>and how much you hate
the person who took them away.</i>

1096
01:37:58.360 --> 01:38:00.070
I added an address in here.

1097
01:38:00.153 --> 01:38:03.615
It might be useful.
It’s an abandoned place outside of town.

1098
01:38:03.698 --> 01:38:06.618
A guy I knew used to do bigger deals there.

1099
01:38:09.496 --> 01:38:10.746
It’s isolated.

1100
01:38:10.831 --> 01:38:12.749
Sounds perfect.

1101
01:38:15.418 --> 01:38:18.713
– Do I owe you any—
– I wasn’t helping you for money.

1102
01:38:18.797 --> 01:38:21.007
– I’m sorry.
– It’s okay.

1103
01:38:21.091 --> 01:38:23.217
See, you have this condition.

1104
01:38:25.220 --> 01:38:29.223
Are you still staying at the Discount Inn,
room 304? You left it at my place.

1105
01:38:34.771 --> 01:38:36.231
Yeah.

1106
01:38:38.108 --> 01:38:40.902
– They treating you okay?
– I don’t remember.

1107
01:38:44.072 --> 01:38:45.782
You know what we have in common?

1108
01:38:47.284 --> 01:38:50.245
We are both survivors.

1109
01:38:52.664 --> 01:38:54.665
You take care, Leonard.

1110
01:39:23.236 --> 01:39:25.280
“Remember Sammy Jankis.”

1111
01:39:34.247 --> 01:39:36.498
“Remember Sammy Jankis.”

1112
01:40:06.112 --> 01:40:08.448
Excuse me, sir.
You left these at your table.

1113
01:40:08.531 --> 01:40:10.241
Thanks.

1114
01:40:11.409 --> 01:40:13.077
– Lincoln Street?
– Yeah.

1115
01:40:13.161 --> 01:40:15.287
Go straight out on Sixth Street.
Go east all the way—

1116
01:40:15.371 --> 01:40:17.582
– Hold on. I’m gonna write this down.
– It’s easy. Just go—

1117
01:40:17.665 --> 01:40:19.625
Trust me. I need to write this down.

1118
01:40:26.632 --> 01:40:28.633
“The Discount Inn.”

1119
01:40:52.408 --> 01:40:54.409
Discount Inn.

1120
01:40:55.370 --> 01:40:57.245
Natalie.

1121
01:40:59.415 --> 01:41:00.625
My car.

1122
01:41:03.044 --> 01:41:04.419
Teddy.

1123
01:41:17.016 --> 01:41:19.267
“John Edward Gammell.”

1124
01:41:21.145 --> 01:41:23.940
This guy told me his name was Teddy.

1125
01:41:27.860 --> 01:41:29.821
“Don’t believe his lies.”

1126
01:41:45.461 --> 01:41:47.255
<i>– Yeah?</i>
– Mr. Gammell?

1127
01:41:47.338 --> 01:41:49.215
<i>– Lenny, is that you?</i>
– John Gammell?

1128
01:41:49.298 --> 01:41:51.717
<i>Lenny, it’s Teddy. Stay there.
I’ll be right over.</i>

1129
01:41:51.801 --> 01:41:53.719
Okay. I’ll be waiting.

1130
01:42:53.404 --> 01:42:55.114
“White. Male.”

1131
01:42:56.574 --> 01:42:58.700
“First name John.”

1132
01:42:58.784 --> 01:43:01.704
“Last name: G” for Gammell.

1133
01:43:07.710 --> 01:43:10.379
“Drugs. License plate.”

1134
01:43:11.714 --> 01:43:13.883
“SG13…

1135
01:43:15.718 --> 01:43:17.803
7IU.”

1136
01:43:22.391 --> 01:43:23.893
It’s him.

1137
01:43:30.066 --> 01:43:32.067
I found you, you fuck.

1138
01:45:29.184 --> 01:45:30.644
– Hi.
– Hi.

1139
01:45:30.728 --> 01:45:33.981
– I’m Mr. Shelby from 304.
– What can I do for you, Leonard?

1140
01:45:35.274 --> 01:45:35.941
Burt.

1141
01:45:36.025 --> 01:45:39.361
Burt. I’m not sure. I think I may have
asked you to hold my calls.

1142
01:45:39.445 --> 01:45:42.281
– You don’t know?
– I think I may have. I’m not good on the phone.

1143
01:45:42.364 --> 01:45:45.033
Right. You said you like to look people
in the eye when you talk to them.

1144
01:45:45.117 --> 01:45:46.535
Yeah.

1145
01:45:46.618 --> 01:45:48.245
You don’t remember saying that?

1146
01:45:48.829 --> 01:45:51.582
– That’s the thing. I have this condition.
– A condition?

1147
01:45:51.665 --> 01:45:54.043
– It’s my memory.
– Amnesia?

1148
01:45:54.126 --> 01:45:56.920
No, no. It’s different from that.
I have no short-term memory.

1149
01:45:57.004 --> 01:45:59.965
I know who I am. I know all about myself.

1150
01:46:00.048 --> 01:46:04.511
Since my injury, I can’t make new memories.
Everything fades.

1151
01:46:04.595 --> 01:46:06.805
If we talk for too long,
I’ll forget how we started.

1152
01:46:06.889 --> 01:46:09.600
Next time I see you,
I’m not gonna remember this conversation.

1153
01:46:10.100 --> 01:46:12.269
I don’t even know if I’ve met you before.

1154
01:46:12.936 --> 01:46:16.440
So, if I seem a little strange
or rude or something—

1155
01:46:18.817 --> 01:46:20.486
I’ve told you this before, haven’t I?

1156
01:46:20.569 --> 01:46:24.655
Yeah. I don’t mean to mess with you,
but it’s so weird.

1157
01:46:24.740 --> 01:46:26.950
– You don’t remember me at all?
– No.

1158
01:46:27.034 --> 01:46:29.870
– We’ve talked a bunch of times.
– I’m sure we have.

1159
01:46:31.038 --> 01:46:32.998
What’s the last thing you remember?

1160
01:46:33.082 --> 01:46:34.582
My wife.

1161
01:46:35.709 --> 01:46:37.461
What’s it like?

1162
01:46:42.090 --> 01:46:45.635
It’s like waking. It’s like you just woke up.

1163
01:46:47.012 --> 01:46:48.931
That must suck.

1164
01:46:49.014 --> 01:46:50.641
It’s all backwards.

1165
01:46:52.392 --> 01:46:55.979
Maybe you get an idea what you want to do next,
but you don’t remember what you just did.

1166
01:46:57.106 --> 01:47:00.901
– I’m exactly the opposite—
– How long have I been staying here?

1167
01:47:00.984 --> 01:47:03.028
– Couple of days.
– And you’re holding my calls?

1168
01:47:03.112 --> 01:47:06.824
– Like you said.
– Okay, but this guy’s an exception.

1169
01:47:07.407 --> 01:47:10.786
– You know this guy?
– Yeah, it’s your friend, right?

1170
01:47:10.869 --> 01:47:12.955
What makes you think he’s my friend?

1171
01:47:13.580 --> 01:47:15.999
– I just saw you together, that’s all.
– He’s not my friend.

1172
01:47:16.083 --> 01:47:18.919
– Okay.
– If he calls or if he shows up here…

1173
01:47:19.002 --> 01:47:20.796
give me a call in my room, okay?

1174
01:47:20.879 --> 01:47:22.464
His name’s Teddy?

1175
01:47:22.548 --> 01:47:24.508
– Teddy, yeah.
– All right.

1176
01:47:25.843 --> 01:47:28.762
Look, I hope my condition’s
not gonna be a problem for you.

1177
01:47:28.846 --> 01:47:31.097
No, not as long as
you remember to pay the bill.

1178
01:47:31.849 --> 01:47:33.308
Yeah. Okay.

1179
01:47:33.851 --> 01:47:35.185
– Forty.
– Forty.

1180
01:47:37.396 --> 01:47:38.438
This guy—

1181
01:47:40.315 --> 01:47:42.234
He’s here already.

1182
01:47:43.402 --> 01:47:45.260
Lenny!

1183
01:47:47.656 --> 01:47:49.156
This guy.

1184
01:47:49.241 --> 01:47:50.491
He’s here already.

1185
01:47:52.369 --> 01:47:53.578
Lenny!

1186
01:47:54.663 --> 01:47:56.038
It’s Leonard…

1187
01:47:57.207 --> 01:47:58.792
like I told you before.

1188
01:47:58.875 --> 01:48:00.876
Did you? I must have forgot.

1189
01:48:02.712 --> 01:48:04.756
I guess I’ve already
told you about my condition.

1190
01:48:04.840 --> 01:48:06.925
Only every time I see you.

1191
01:48:16.518 --> 01:48:18.562
– My car.
– This <i>is</i> your car.

1192
01:48:18.645 --> 01:48:20.689
You’re in a playful mood.

1193
01:48:22.232 --> 01:48:24.067
It’s not good to make fun
of someone’s handicap.

1194
01:48:24.651 --> 01:48:26.902
Just trying to have a little fun.

1195
01:48:33.368 --> 01:48:35.369
Roll up your window.

1196
01:48:41.418 --> 01:48:43.419
– It’s broken.
– I can get that fixed for you.

1197
01:48:45.547 --> 01:48:48.466
– So where to, Sherlock?
– I got a lead on a place.

1198
01:48:48.550 --> 01:48:50.468
What the hell you wanna go there for?

1199
01:48:50.552 --> 01:48:52.928
– You know it?
– Yeah. It’s just this fucked-up building.

1200
01:48:53.013 --> 01:48:56.308
– Why do you wanna go there?
– Don’t remember.

1201
01:49:17.037 --> 01:49:20.165
– Looks like somebody’s home.
– That thing’s been here for years.

1202
01:49:23.585 --> 01:49:26.463
What are you talking about?
These tracks are only a few days old.

1203
01:49:26.546 --> 01:49:29.216
Tracks? What are you? Pocahontas?

1204
01:49:31.009 --> 01:49:32.259
Come on!

1205
01:49:40.185 --> 01:49:42.103
Let’s take a look inside.

1206
01:49:59.955 --> 01:50:01.248
“Teddy.”

1207
01:50:02.123 --> 01:50:06.251
“Don’t believe his lies.
He is the one. Kill him.”

1208
01:50:06.336 --> 01:50:10.090
I finally found him.
How long have I been looking?

1209
01:50:11.967 --> 01:50:13.134
Find anything?

1210
01:50:14.761 --> 01:50:16.346
Didn’t think so.

1211
01:50:16.429 --> 01:50:17.806
Let’s go.

1212
01:50:18.348 --> 01:50:19.723
Fuck this.

1213
01:50:21.893 --> 01:50:23.687
You’re gonna pay for what you did.

1214
01:50:23.770 --> 01:50:26.815
– Beg forgiveness, and then you pay.
– Leonard.

1215
01:50:30.485 --> 01:50:32.946
You don’t have a clue, you freak.

1216
01:50:33.029 --> 01:50:37.325
Beg my wife’s forgiveness
before I blow your brains out.

1217
01:50:37.409 --> 01:50:40.370
Leonard, you don’t know what’s going on.

1218
01:50:40.453 --> 01:50:42.914
– You don’t even know my name.
– Teddy.

1219
01:50:42.998 --> 01:50:45.166
That’s ’cause you read it
off a fucking picture.

1220
01:50:46.167 --> 01:50:48.545
You don’t know who you are.

1221
01:50:48.628 --> 01:50:51.256
I’m Leonard Shelby. I’m from San Francisco.

1222
01:50:51.339 --> 01:50:55.176
That’s who you were.
That’s not what you’ve become.

1223
01:50:55.260 --> 01:50:57.761
– Shut your mouth.
– You want to know, Lenny?

1224
01:50:57.846 --> 01:50:59.139
Come on.

1225
01:50:59.222 --> 01:51:01.016
Come on. Let’s go down to the basement.

1226
01:51:02.017 --> 01:51:04.102
Let’s go down, you and me, together.

1227
01:51:04.185 --> 01:51:06.186
Then you’ll know who you really are.

1228
01:51:10.525 --> 01:51:11.693
No!

